Born in [[Perry, Georgia]], he began studies at the [[United States Military Academy]] but dropped out after being found deficient in geometry. He joined the Army in 1906, rose through the [[non-commissioned officer]] ranks, and obtained a commission after passing an examination in 1909. As a young man, Hodges served under [[John J. Pershing]] in the [[Pancho Villa Expedition]] and became part of the first rescue mission in U.S. military aviation history when he helped save a stranded aviator. He was a [[battalion commander]] in [[France]] during [[World War I]] and was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United States)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for his heroism.
He would have graduated with the Class of 1909, but he dropped out after the first year because of an inability to comprehend geometry. He then worked at a grocery store for a year.{{sfn|Hannan|1999|p=397}}
In 1906, Hodges enlisted in the [[United States Army]] as a [[Private (rank)|private]] and was assigned to Company L, [[17th Infantry Regiment (United States)|17th Infantry]] at [[Fort McPherson]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].{{sfn|Hannan|1999|p=397}} He promoted to the rank of [[Sergeant#United States|sergeant]], and in 1909, he performed well on the examination for prospective officers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Biographical Note, Courtney Hicks Hodges |url=https://uat.research.archives.gov/id/10679495 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230726205120/https://uat.research.archives.gov/id/10679495 |archive-date=26 July 2023 |access-date=26 October 2020 |website=National Archives Catalog |publisher=National Archives and Records Administration |location=College Park, MD}}</ref> He was appointed a [[Second lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]] of [[Infantry Branch (United States)|Infantry]] in November, just a few months after his [[West Point]] classmates graduated, and was assigned to the [[13th Infantry Regiment (United States)|13th Infantry]].{{sfn|Sylvan|Smith|2008|p=1}}<ref>{{cite magazine |editor1-last=Lincoln |editor1-first=Natalie Sumner |date=June 1921 |title=Work of the Chapters: General Stewart Chapter |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aO1RAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA341 |magazine=Daughters of the American Revolution Magazine |location=Washington, DC |publisher=Daughters of the American Revolution |page=341 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Early in his career, while stationed in the [[Philippines]], he served with the future [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Army Chief of Staff]], [[George C. Marshall]], and later, while stationed in [[Mexico]], he served with future General [[George S. Patton]].{{sfn|English|2009|p=95}}{{sfn|Wishnevsky|2006|pages=22-23}}
Hodges served with the [[6th Infantry Regiment (United States)|6th Infantry Regiment]], [[5th Infantry Division (United States)|5th Division]], during [[World War I]], which America entered in April 1917 (see [[American entry into World War I]]). He was promoted to [[Lieutenant colonel

